					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">You can do n-bit by n-bit multiplication using a 2^(n + 1)-entry lookup table. Start with some algebra:
<br />
<br />a^2 + b^2 + 2ab = (a + b)^2
<br />2ab = (a + b)^2 - a^2 - b^2
<br />ab = (a + b)^2/2 - a^2/2 - b^2/2
<br />
<br />So you'd have a table of (a^2)/2 for a = 0 to 30, and then compute (a + b)^2, a^2, and b^2. It could be as easy as this (untested):
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">scale_volume:<br />&nbsp; clc<br />&nbsp; lda env_volume<br />&nbsp; adc note_volume<br />&nbsp; tax<br />&nbsp; lda squared,x<br />&nbsp; sec<br />&nbsp; ldx env_volume<br />&nbsp; sbc squared,x<br />&nbsp; ldx note_volume<br />&nbsp; sbc squared,x<br /><br />&nbsp; ; divide result by 16 and round up<br />&nbsp; lsr a<br />&nbsp; lsr a<br />&nbsp; lsr a<br />&nbsp; lsr a<br />&nbsp; adc #0<br />&nbsp; rts<br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
